Deep in the shadows of Mt. Hood, a beautiful apparition reveals itself to the few who seek it. I’ve been looking at these falls from a popular vantage point for many years. After studying the maps and topography, I set out on a day of bushwhacking through the dense forest. Several hours into scrambling along the creek, I found myself at the base of the roaring cascade. I spent the afternoon in solitude, perched among the vibrations of the crashing stream.

Dude was the size of a damn Prius, kodiak bears are on another level. Their isolation on the archipelago has evolutionarily refined them into a much larger subspecies of a normal brown bear. This encounter happened within minutes of leaving the airport. Not sure if I’ll ever make it back to Kodiak, but the wildlife experiences I had there were unmatched.

Under most cases I find keeping a relatively fast shutter speed for larger waterfalls retains their scale better. However, I also find the foreground can become too busy if that’s the case. Best of both worlds on this shot. I blended a slower shutter for the foreground to create a softer texture that retained the cooler tones of the McKenzie river, and a fast shutter to freeze the falls and convey their massive energy.
